# Node.js HTTP — req.url, req.method, res.end(), and Redirection

This project demonstrates core `http` module concepts in Node.js:
handling different routes with `req.url`, handling different request
types with `req.method`, ending responses with `res.end()`, and
performing redirection using status codes + headers.

See `node_http_concepts.pdf` in this folder for detailed explanations
of each concept with code examples and summary tables.

## What `server.js` covers

### 1. `req.url`
Gives the path portion of the requested URL (e.g. `/`, `/about`,
`/users`). Used to decide which route logic should run.

### 2. `req.method`
Gives the HTTP method used (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc). Combined
with `req.url`, the same path can behave differently based on the
method — this is the foundation of REST APIs.

### 3. `res.end()`
Ends the response and optionally sends final data. Every response
**must** call `res.end()` at some point, or the client will keep
waiting/loading forever.

### 4. Redirection
Achieved using a 3xx status code (like `301`) along with a `Location`
header. The browser sees this and automatically re-requests the new
URL.

## Routes in this server

| Route | Method | Behavior |
|---|---|---|
| `/` | GET | Returns "Welcome to the Home Page" |
| `/old-page` | any | Redirects (301) to `/new-page` |
| `/new-page` | GET | Returns "You have reached the New Page!" |
| `/users` | GET | Returns "Fetching all users" |
| `/users` | POST | Returns "New user created" |
| anything else | any | Returns 404 "Page Not Found" |

## How to Run

```bash
node server.js
```

Then test these in your browser or with a tool like Postman:

- `http://localhost:3000/` → Home page
- `http://localhost:3000/old-page` → Watch it redirect to `/new-page`
  (check the address bar — it changes automatically)
- `http://localhost:3000/users` → GET returns one message
- POST to `http://localhost:3000/users` (via Postman/curl) → returns
  a different message, same URL

Testing POST from a browser directly isn't possible (browsers only
do GET when you type a URL), so use Postman or curl:

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/users
```

## Key Takeaways

- `req.url` + `req.method` together decide how a server responds —
  this pattern is exactly what routing frameworks like Express
  automate for you.
- `res.end()` is mandatory to close every response.
- Redirection is just a status code (301/302) + a `Location` header —
  nothing magical, the browser does the actual re-requesting.

## Possible Improvements

- Move to Express.js: `app.get()`, `app.post()`, and
  `res.redirect('/new-page')` replace all the manual `if/else` checks
  here with much shorter code.
- Add query string parsing using `req.url` with the `url` module
  (`new URL(req.url, 'http://localhost:3000')`) to handle URLs like
  `/search?q=node`.
- Add proper error handling for unsupported methods per route.